The optimal portfolio rule is the one identified in proposition 2. Once in a losing position, the investor becomes risk loving and therefore is always willing to invest in stocks (since they have a higher expected return and higher risk than the safe asset). For levels of wealth belowW, marginal utility is again decreasing, and this eventually imposes a limit on the amount of risk the investor is willing to take. The sign of
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $( \partial \alpha ^{*}_{1}/\partial P_{1}) \vert _{R^{+},R^{-}}$ \end{document}
